('Sarcoidosis - Cardiac Involvement', 'Corticosteroids (Prednisone). May require pacemaker/ICD if conduction disease/arrhythmias present. Monitor with EKG, Echo, Cardiac MRI/PET.', 'Sulfa', 'Prednisone taper, Metoprolol for arrhythmia', 'Cardiac MRI shows inflammation/scarring. EKG shows heart block.', 'Managed by Cardiology and Pulmonology.'),
('Tuberous Sclerosis Complex with Renal Angiomyolipomas', 'Everolimus (mTOR inhibitor) to shrink angiomyolipomas. Monitor renal function, tumor size (MRI/US annually). Manage other TSC manifestations (seizures, skin).', 'NKDA', 'Everolimus 10mg PO daily', 'Renal Ultrasound shows bilateral large angiomyolipomas', 'Nephrology consulted regarding risk of hemorrhage.'),
('Von Hippel-Lindau Disease with Retinal Hemangioblastoma', 'Laser photocoagulation or cryotherapy for retinal hemangioblastoma by Ophthalmology. Continued surveillance for other VHL tumors.', 'NKDA', 'None currently', 'Ophthalmology exam confirmed retinal angioma', 'Annual screening protocol in place.'),
('MEN1 with Hyperparathyroidism', 'Subtotal or total parathyroidectomy recommended. Monitor Calcium/PTH levels. Continue screening for pancreatic NETs and pituitary adenomas.', 'NKDA', 'Calcium/Vit D post-op if needed', 'Elevated Calcium and PTH. Neck US showed parathyroid hyperplasia.', 'Surgery scheduled.'),
('MEN2A Post-Thyroidectomy', 'Levothyroxine replacement therapy. Annual screening for pheochromocytoma (plasma metanephrines) and hyperparathyroidism (Calcium/PTH).', 'NKDA', 'Levothyroxine 125mcg PO daily', 'Calcitonin undetectable. Metanephrines normal.', 'Lifelong surveillance required.'),
('Acromegaly - Post-Surgical Remission', 'Monitor IGF-1 levels annually. Pituitary MRI periodically. Assess for residual hypopituitarism and replace hormones as needed.', 'NKDA', 'Hydrocortisone 10mg AM / 5mg PM (adrenal insufficiency)', 'IGF-1 level normalized post-surgery', 'Patient reports improvement in acromegalic features.'),
('Cushing Disease - Post-Surgical Remission (Hypocortisolism)', 'Hydrocortisone replacement therapy, taper slowly over months as HPA axis recovers. Monitor morning cortisol levels and symptoms.', 'NKDA', 'Hydrocortisone 10mg AM / 5mg PM (tapering)', 'Morning Cortisol low post-op', 'Patient educated on stress dosing.'),
('Pheochromocytoma - Post-Adrenalectomy', 'Monitor blood pressure and plasma/urine metanephrines periodically to assess for recurrence or metastases.', 'NKDA', 'None related to pheo currently', 'Post-op metanephrines normalized', 'Patient recovered well from surgery.'),
('Congenital Adrenal Hyperplasia - Adult Management', 'Continue Hydrocortisone/Fludrocortisone. Monitor 17-OHP, androstenedione, testosterone levels. Adjust doses for optimal hormone balance and growth (if applicable). Fertility counseling.', 'NKDA', 'Hydrocortisone dose adjusted, Fludrocortisone daily', 'Hormone levels checked quarterly', 'Managed by Endocrinology.'),
('Addison Disease - Sick Day Management', 'Patient educated on stress dosing protocol (double or triple Hydrocortisone dose) during illness/fever/stress. Medical alert bracelet worn. Emergency hydrocortisone injection kit prescribed.', 'NKDA', 'Hydrocortisone, Fludrocortisone (home meds)', 'N/A', 'Reinforced importance of seeking medical attention if unable to take oral meds.'),
('Central Diabetes Insipidus - Stable on DDAVP', 'Continue DDAVP nasal spray nightly. Monitor for hyponatremia (if dose too high) or hypernatremia/polyuria (if dose too low). Check serum sodium periodically.', 'NKDA', 'DDAVP nasal spray 1 spray QHS', 'Serum Sodium WNL', 'Patient reports good control of thirst/urination.'),
('Nephrogenic Diabetes Insipidus - Managed', 'Continue low sodium diet, HCTZ. Ensure free access to water. Monitor urine output, serum sodium, renal function.', 'NKDA', 'Hydrochlorothiazide 25mg daily', 'Serum Sodium stable', 'Symptoms reasonably controlled with current regimen.'),
('SIADH - Chronic (e.g., due to malignancy)', 'Fluid restriction remains key. Consider Urea or Tolvaptan for persistent hyponatremia if symptomatic or severe. Treat underlying cause if possible.', 'NKDA', 'Fluid restriction (<1.2 L/day). Urea powder trial initiated.', 'Serum Sodium low-normal range', 'Patient managing fluid restriction at home.'),
('Prolactinoma - Stable on Cabergoline', 'Continue Cabergoline. Monitor prolactin levels and pituitary MRI annually (or less frequently if stable). Assess for medication side effects.', 'NKDA', 'Cabergoline 0.5mg PO twice weekly', 'Prolactin normalized. MRI shows slight shrinkage of adenoma.', 'Patient tolerating medication well.'),
('Hypopituitarism - Stable Replacement', 'Continue Levothyroxine, Hydrocortisone, Testosterone/Estrogen. Monitor hormone levels periodically (TSH not reliable, use Free T4). Ensure patient understands stress dosing/sick day rules.', 'NKDA', 'Levothyroxine, Hydrocortisone, Estradiol patch', 'Free T4, Cortisol, Estradiol levels appropriate', 'Patient stable on replacement therapy.'),
('Paget Disease of Bone - Remission after Bisphosphonate', 'Monitor Alkaline Phosphatase annually. Repeat treatment (Zoledronic Acid IV) if Alk Phos rises significantly or new symptoms develop. Maintain adequate Calcium/Vit D intake.', 'NKDA', 'Calcium/Vit D daily', 'Alkaline Phosphatase normalized', 'Patient asymptomatic.'),
('Neutropenic Fever - Resolved', 'Completed course of IV antibiotics. ANC recovered (>500). Discharged home with close Oncology follow-up.', 'Penicillin', 'None currently (antibiotics finished)', 'ANC > 1500/uL', 'Patient afebrile. Source of infection unclear.'),
('Spinal Cord Injury - Chronic Management (Paraplegia)', 'Manage neurogenic bowel/bladder (bowel program, intermittent catheterization). Prevent pressure ulcers (skin checks, appropriate cushion/mattress). Manage spasticity (Baclofen). PT/OT for maintenance. Annual renal US.', 'Latex', 'Oxybutynin, Baclofen, Polyethylene glycol', 'Annual renal ultrasound WNL', 'Patient independent with self-care using adaptive equipment.'),
('Subarachnoid Hemorrhage - Post Coiling/Clipping', 'Follow-up cerebral angiography/MRA per protocol. Monitor neurological status. Manage potential complications (hydrocephalus, vasospasm - though Nimodipine completed). Cognitive/physical rehab ongoing.', 'NKDA', 'Levetiracetam (seizure prophylaxis short term)', 'Follow-up MRA shows successful aneurysm treatment', 'Patient participating in rehabilitation therapies.'),
('Malaria - Uncomplicated (Vivax/Ovale)', 'Chloroquine treatment regimen (if sensitive region) OR alternative (Atovaquone/Proguanil). PLUS Primaquine for radical cure (to prevent relapse - MUST check G6PD status first).', 'NKDA', 'Chloroquine PO regimen completed. G6PD normal. Primaquine PO daily x 14d started.', 'Blood smears positive for P. vivax', 'Patient educated on importance of completing Primaquine.'),
('Malaria Prophylaxis', 'Prescribed appropriate medication based on travel destination/duration/resistance patterns (e.g., Atovaquone/Proguanil, Doxycycline, Mefloquine). Counseled on adherence and mosquito bite prevention.', 'NKDA', 'Atovaquone/Proguanil (Malarone) 1 tab PO daily starting 1 day prior to travel', 'N/A', 'Patient traveling to malaria-endemic region.'),
('Tuberculosis, Active Pulmonary', 'Standard 4-drug RIPE therapy (Rifampin, Isoniazid, Pyrazinamide, Ethambutol) x 2 months, followed by 2-drug (RI) continuation phase x 4 months. Directly Observed Therapy (DOT) recommended. Monthly sputum cultures until negative. Monitor LFTs, vision (Ethambutol).', 'NKDA', 'Rifampin, Isoniazid (+B6), Pyrazinamide, Ethambutol daily (DOT)', 'Sputum AFB smear positive. Culture pending. Chest X-ray shows cavitation.', 'Patient started on treatment. Public health notified.'),
('Chikungunya Fever', 'Supportive care: Rest, fluids, analgesics (Acetaminophen, NSAIDs) for fever and severe joint pain. PT may be needed for persistent arthralgias.', 'NKDA', 'Acetaminophen PRN fever/pain', 'Chikungunya IgM antibody positive', 'Patient recently traveled to endemic area. Reports fever, rash, severe polyarthralgias.'),
('Dengue Fever', 'Supportive care: Rest, fluids, Acetaminophen for fever/pain. AVOID NSAIDs/Aspirin (increased bleeding risk). Monitor for warning signs (abdominal pain, persistent vomiting, bleeding, lethargy) indicating severe dengue.', 'Aspirin, NSAIDs', 'Acetaminophen PRN', 'Dengue NS1 antigen positive or IgM positive', 'Patient advised on hydration and warning signs requiring immediate medical attention.'),
('Zika Virus Infection', 'Supportive care: Rest, fluids, Acetaminophen for fever/pain. Counsel on preventing sexual transmission. Special considerations for pregnant women (risk of microcephaly).', 'NKDA', 'Acetaminophen PRN', 'Zika virus RNA or IgM antibody positive', 'Patient recently traveled to endemic area. Reports rash, fever, conjunctivitis.'),
('West Nile Virus Infection', 'Supportive care for mild cases (fever, headache). Hospitalization for neuroinvasive disease (meningitis, encephalitis, paralysis) with supportive management.', 'NKDA', 'Supportive care only', 'West Nile virus IgM antibody positive in CSF (for neuroinvasive disease)', 'Most infections are asymptomatic or mild.'),
('Rocky Mountain Spotted Fever (RMSF)', 'Doxycycline IV or PO STAT (treatment of choice for all ages). Do NOT wait for confirmatory testing if suspected. Treat empirically.', 'NKDA', 'Doxycycline 100mg PO BID initiated empirically', 'Clinical suspicion based on fever, headache, rash (often starts wrists/ankles, spreads centrally), tick exposure history', 'Serious illness requiring prompt treatment.'),
('Ehrlichiosis / Anaplasmosis', 'Doxycycline IV or PO treatment of choice.', 'NKDA', 'Doxycycline 100mg PO BID x 10-14d', 'Tick exposure history. Presents with fever, malaise, headache, myalgias, cytopenias (leukopenia, thrombocytopenia). Serology or PCR confirms.', 'Tick-borne bacterial infections.'),
('Babesiosis', 'Atovaquone + Azithromycin combination therapy. Consider Clindamycin + Quinine for severe disease. Exchange transfusion if high parasitemia/severe hemolysis.', 'NKDA', 'Atovaquone + Azithromycin PO', 'Blood smear shows intraerythrocytic ring forms (Maltese cross). PCR confirms.', 'Tick-borne parasitic infection, endemic in Northeast US.'),
('Leptospirosis', 'Mild: Doxycycline PO. Severe (Weil disease - jaundice, renal failure, hemorrhage): Penicillin G IV or Ceftriaxone IV. Supportive care crucial.', 'Penicillin (use Doxycycline)', 'Doxycycline 100mg PO BID', 'Exposure to animal urine/contaminated water. Presents with fever, myalgias, headache, conjunctival suffusion +/- jaundice, AKI.', 'Serology confirms diagnosis.'),
('Brucellosis', 'Combination antibiotic therapy for several weeks (e.g., Doxycycline + Rifampin OR Doxycycline + Streptomycin/Gentamicin).', 'NKDA', 'Doxycycline + Rifampin PO', 'Exposure to unpasteurized dairy or infected animals. Presents with undulant fever, sweats, arthralgias, hepatosplenomegaly. Blood cultures or serology positive.', 'Requires prolonged antibiotic course.'),
('Q Fever (Coxiella burnetii)', 'Acute: Doxycycline PO. Chronic (endocarditis): Doxycycline + Hydroxychloroquine for prolonged duration (>=18 months).', 'NKDA', 'Doxycycline 100mg PO BID x 14d (for acute)', 'Exposure to infected animals (sheep, goats, cattle). Presents as atypical pneumonia or flu-like illness (acute) or culture-negative endocarditis (chronic). Serology confirms.', 'Consider in patients with relevant exposures.'),
('Typhoid Fever (Salmonella Typhi)', 'Fluoroquinolone (Ciprofloxacin) or Ceftriaxone or Azithromycin (based on susceptibility). Supportive care, hydration.', 'NKDA', 'Ciprofloxacin 500mg PO BID x 7-14d', 'Travel to endemic area. Presents with sustained high fever, headache, abdominal pain, relative bradycardia, rose spots (sometimes). Blood/stool cultures positive.', 'Reportable illness.'),
('Cholera (Vibrio cholerae)', 'Aggressive oral or IV rehydration is cornerstone of treatment. Antibiotics (Doxycycline, Azithromycin, Ciprofloxacin) can shorten duration/reduce shedding but secondary to hydration.', 'NKDA', 'Aggressive IV Fluid resuscitation with Lactated Ringers. Doxycycline single dose.', 'Exposure to contaminated water/food in endemic area. Presents with profuse watery "rice water" diarrhea, rapid dehydration.', 'Severe dehydration can be fatal quickly.'),
('Amebiasis (Entamoeba histolytica)', 'Asymptomatic cyst passers: Luminal agent (Paromomycin or Iodoquinol). Intestinal disease or Liver Abscess: Metronidazole or Tinidazole followed by a luminal agent.', 'NKDA', 'Metronidazole 500-750mg PO TID followed by Paromomycin', 'Stool O&P may show cysts/trophozoites. Serology positive for invasive disease. Liver abscess seen on imaging.', 'Protozoal infection.'),
('Giardiasis (Giardia lamblia)', 'Metronidazole or Tinidazole or Nitazoxanide.', 'NKDA', 'Tinidazole 2g PO single dose', 'Stool O&P or antigen assay positive for Giardia', 'Common cause of waterborne diarrheal illness (foul smelling, fatty stools).'),
('Cryptosporidiosis', 'Supportive care, hydration. Nitazoxanide may shorten duration in immunocompetent hosts. Effective ART crucial in HIV patients.', 'NKDA', 'Nitazoxanide 500mg PO BID x 3d', 'Stool O&P (modified acid-fast stain) or antigen assay positive', 'Protozoal infection causing watery diarrhea.'),
('Hookworm Infection', 'Albendazole or Mebendazole.', 'NKDA', 'Albendazole 400mg PO single dose', 'Stool O&P positive for hookworm eggs', 'Can cause iron deficiency anemia.'),
('Ascariasis (Ascaris lumbricoides)', 'Albendazole or Mebendazole.', 'NKDA', 'Mebendazole 100mg PO BID x 3d', 'Stool O&P positive for Ascaris eggs or passage of adult worm', 'Large intestinal roundworm.'),
('Trichuriasis (Trichuris trichiura - Whipworm)', 'Mebendazole or Albendazole (often requires longer course/higher dose than for Ascaris/hookworm).', 'NKDA', 'Mebendazole 100mg PO BID x 3d', 'Stool O&P positive for whipworm eggs', 'Intestinal nematode.'),
('Strongyloidiasis (Strongyloides stercoralis)', 'Ivermectin treatment of choice. Albendazole alternative.', 'NKDA', 'Ivermectin 200mcg/kg PO daily x 1-2 days', 'Stool O&P (larvae) or serology positive', 'Can cause hyperinfection syndrome in immunocompromised hosts.'),
('Schistosomiasis', 'Praziquantel treatment of choice.', 'NKDA', 'Praziquantel PO dose based on weight/species', 'Stool or urine O&P positive for Schistosoma eggs. Serology useful for travelers.', 'Fluke infection acquired through freshwater contact in endemic areas.'),
('Neurocysticercosis (Taenia solium larvae in brain)', 'Treatment depends on stage/location/number of cysts: Albendazole + Corticosteroids often used for viable cysts. Seizure management.', 'NKDA', 'Albendazole + Prednisone, Levetiracetam for seizures', 'MRI/CT Brain shows characteristic cystic lesions +/- calcifications. Serology may support diagnosis.', 'Common cause of adult-onset seizures in endemic areas.'),
('Leprosy (Hansen Disease)', 'Multidrug therapy (MDT) based on classification (paucibacillary vs multibacillary) - typically Rifampin, Dapsone, Clofazimine for months-years.', 'Sulfa (Monitor Dapsone use carefully)', 'Rifampin + Dapsone + Clofazimine daily (multibacillary MDT)', 'Clinical diagnosis confirmed by skin biopsy showing acid-fast bacilli or characteristic granulomas', 'Managed by infectious disease/dermatology specialists.'),
('Chagas Disease (Trypanosoma cruzi)', 'Acute phase/Congenital: Benznidazole or Nifurtimox. Chronic phase: Treatment may prevent progression but doesn risk; decision individualized. Manage cardiac/GI complications.', 'NKDA', 'Benznidazole trial considered for chronic phase', 'Serology positive for T. cruzi. EKG/Echo may show cardiomyopathy.', 'Endemic in Latin America. Can cause cardiomyopathy and megacolon/megaesophagus decades later.'),
('Leishmaniasis - Cutaneous', 'Treatment varies by species/location/severity: Observation, topical Paromomycin, cryotherapy, intralesional/systemic antimonials (Sodium Stibogluconate), Miltefosine, Amphotericin B.', 'NKDA', 'Observation for simple lesion', 'Travel to endemic area. Skin biopsy shows Leishmania amastigotes. PCR confirms species.', 'Protozoal infection transmitted by sandflies.'),
('Leishmaniasis - Visceral (Kala-azar)', 'Systemic treatment required: Liposomal Amphotericin B preferred. Miltefosine, Paromomycin, Antimonials alternatives.', 'NKDA', 'Liposomal Amphotericin B IV infusions', 'Travel to endemic area. Presents with prolonged fever, weight loss, massive splenomegaly, pancytopenia. Bone marrow aspirate/biopsy shows amastigotes.', 'Serious systemic infection.'),
('African Trypanosomiasis (Sleeping Sickness) - Hemolymphatic Stage', 'Pentamidine (T.b. gambiense) or Suramin (T.b. rhodesiense).', 'NKDA', 'Pentamidine IV infusions', 'Travel to endemic Africa. Trypanosomes seen in blood smear or lymph node aspirate. CSF analysis normal.', 'Transmitted by tsetse fly.'),
('African Trypanosomiasis (Sleeping Sickness) - CNS Stage', 'Eflornithine (+/- Nifurtimox - NECT) for T.b. gambiense. Melarsoprol for T.b. rhodesiense (toxic).', 'NKDA', 'Eflornithine IV infusions (NECT regimen)', 'CSF analysis shows trypanosomes or elevated WBC/protein', 'Requires drugs that cross blood-brain barrier.'),
('Rabies', 'Post-exposure prophylaxis (PEP) crucial BEFORE symptom onset (Rabies vaccine series + Rabies Immune Globulin - RIG). Once symptoms develop, disease is almost invariably fatal; supportive care only.', 'NKDA', 'Rabies PEP initiated immediately after exposure', 'Animal bite from potentially rabid animal (bat, raccoon, unvaccinated dog). OR Symptomatic patient (hydrophobia, aerophobia, paralysis, encephalitis) - diagnosis often clinical/postmortem.', 'Prevention is key.'),
('Tetanus', 'Supportive care in ICU: Airway management, muscle relaxants (benzodiazepines), control spasms. Metronidazole or Penicillin G to eradicate C. tetani. Tetanus Immune Globulin (TIG) administered. Wound debridement.', 'NKDA', 'Diazepam IV infusion, Metronidazole IV, TIG IM', 'Clinical diagnosis: Trismus (lockjaw), muscle rigidity, opisthotonus, spasms, often after puncture wound', 'Preventable by vaccination.'),
('Botulism', 'Supportive care (mechanical ventilation often required). Antitoxin administration (Equine botulinum antitoxin or BabyBIG for infants). Identify/remove source (contaminated food, wound).', 'NKDA', 'Botulinum Antitoxin administered', 'Clinical diagnosis: Acute descending symmetric flaccid paralysis, cranial nerve palsies (diplopia, dysphagia, dysarthria), afebrile', 'Foodborne, wound, and infant forms exist.'),
('Diphtheria', 'Diphtheria antitoxin administration STAT. Antibiotics (Erythromycin or Penicillin G) to eradicate C. diphtheriae and prevent spread. Respiratory isolation. Airway management PRN.', 'Penicillin (use Erythromycin)', 'Diphtheria Antitoxin administered, Erythromycin IV/PO', 'Clinical diagnosis: Sore throat, fever, adherent gray pseudomembrane in pharynx, potential for airway obstruction/myocarditis/neuropathy', 'Preventable by vaccination.'),
('Pertussis (Whooping Cough)', 'Macrolide antibiotic (Azithromycin, Erythromycin, Clarithromycin) to decrease infectivity (most effective early). Supportive care for cough. Respiratory isolation.', 'NKDA', 'Azithromycin PO x 5 days', 'Clinical diagnosis: Paroxysmal cough followed by inspiratory "whoop", post-tussive emesis. PCR or culture confirms.', 'Preventable by vaccination. Cocooning infants important.'),
('Measles (Rubeola)', 'Supportive care: Fluids, rest, Acetaminophen/Ibuprofen. Vitamin A supplementation recommended (reduces morbidity/mortality). Respiratory isolation.', 'NKDA', 'Vitamin A PO x 2 doses', 'Clinical diagnosis: Prodrome (cough, coryza, conjunctivitis), Koplik spots, followed by maculopapular rash spreading cephalocaudally', 'Highly contagious, preventable by vaccination.'),
('Mumps', 'Supportive care: Analgesics for pain/fever, warm/cold compresses for parotid swelling. Respiratory isolation.', 'NKDA', 'Acetaminophen PRN', 'Clinical diagnosis: Parotitis (unilateral or bilateral). Serology or PCR confirms.', 'Potential complications: Orchitis, meningitis, pancreatitis. Preventable by vaccination.'),
('Rubella (German Measles)', 'Supportive care. Respiratory isolation. Generally mild illness. Major risk is Congenital Rubella Syndrome if acquired during pregnancy.', 'NKDA', 'Acetaminophen PRN', 'Clinical diagnosis: Mild fever, lymphadenopathy (postauricular, occipital), maculopapular rash spreads rapidly. Serology confirms.', 'Preventable by vaccination.'),
('Varicella (Chickenpox)', 'Supportive care: Antihistamines/Calamine lotion for itching, Acetaminophen for fever (AVOID Aspirin - Reye syndrome risk). Acyclovir considered for adolescents/adults or high-risk individuals if started early.', 'Aspirin', 'Diphenhydramine PO PRN itching, Acetaminophen PRN fever', 'Clinical diagnosis: Generalized pruritic vesicular rash ("dewdrop on a rose petal"), lesions in various stages', 'Highly contagious, preventable by vaccination.'),
('Smallpox (Variola)', 'Historical disease - eradicated globally. If re-emerged: Strict isolation, supportive care, Tecovirimat antiviral. Vaccination crucial for contacts/responders.', 'NKDA', 'N/A (eradicated)', 'N/A', 'Included for historical context/bioterrorism awareness.'),
('Anthrax - Cutaneous', 'Antibiotics (Ciprofloxacin or Doxycycline) PO for 60 days.', 'NKDA', 'Ciprofloxacin 500mg PO BID x 60d', 'Painless eschar with surrounding edema after exposure. Gram stain/culture/PCR confirms B. anthracis.', 'Treat promptly.'),
('Anthrax - Inhalational', 'Multi-drug IV antibiotic regimen (e.g., Ciprofloxacin + Meropenem + Linezolid) PLUS Anthrax Antitoxin (Raxibacumab or Obiltoxaximab). Supportive care in ICU.', 'NKDA', 'IV Ciprofloxacin + Meropenem + Linezolid, Raxibacumab', 'Flu-like prodrome followed by rapid respiratory failure/shock. Widened mediastinum on CXR. Exposure history.', 'High mortality bioterrorism agent.'),
('Plague - Bubonic (Yersinia pestis)', 'Streptomycin IM or Gentamicin IV treatment of choice. Doxycycline or Fluoroquinolone alternatives. Drain buboes if necessary. Droplet precautions until pneumonia ruled out.', 'NKDA', 'Gentamicin IV', 'Sudden onset fever, chills, weakness, painful swollen lymph node (bubo). Exposure to fleas/rodents in endemic area. Aspirate/blood culture confirms.', 'Treat promptly.'),
('Plague - Pneumonic', 'Respiratory isolation crucial! Streptomycin IM or Gentamicin IV. Treat promptly (high mortality, contagious). Prophylaxis for contacts (Doxycycline).', 'NKDA', 'Gentamicin IV', 'Develops from bubonic plague or inhalation. Presents with fever, cough, bloody sputum, respiratory failure.', 'Bioterrorism agent.'),
('Tularemia (Francisella tularensis)', 'Streptomycin IM or Gentamicin IV treatment of choice. Doxycycline or Ciprofloxacin alternatives. Treatment duration 10-14 days.', 'NKDA', 'Gentamicin IV', 'Exposure to rabbits, ticks, deer flies. Presents variably: Ulceroglandular (ulcer + lymphadenopathy), pneumonic, typhoidal. Serology confirms.', 'Potential bioterrorism agent.'),
('Viral Hemorrhagic Fever (e.g., Ebola, Marburg, Lassa)', 'Strict barrier nursing/isolation precautions! Supportive care is mainstay (aggressive fluids, electrolyte management, hemodynamic support). Ribavirin may have role in Lassa/CCHF. Experimental therapies may be available.', 'NKDA', 'Supportive care, IV Fluids', 'Travel to endemic area. Abrupt onset fever, malaise, myalgia, followed by GI symptoms, hemorrhage, shock. Specific PCR/serology confirms.', 'High mortality, public health emergency.'),
('Periodic Fever Syndrome (e.g., PFAPA - Periodic Fever, Aphthous Stomatitis, Pharyngitis, Adenitis)', 'Short course of Corticosteroids (Prednisone) at onset of episode often aborts fever. Cimetidine or Colchicine prophylaxis sometimes used. Tonsillectomy may be curative.', 'NKDA', 'Prednisone 1-2mg/kg x1 dose at fever onset', 'Clinical diagnosis based on recurrent predictable episodes in young children', 'Benign, usually resolves spontaneously by adolescence.'),
('Kawasaki Disease', 'IVIG (high dose) + Aspirin (high dose initially, then low dose). Echocardiogram baseline and follow-up to screen for coronary artery aneurysms.', 'Aspirin (use only under guidance for Kawasaki)', 'IVIG 2g/kg x1 dose, Aspirin high dose initially', 'Clinical diagnosis based on criteria: Fever >5 days + 4/5 (Conjunctivitis, Rash, Adenopathy, Strawberry tongue/lip changes, Hand/foot edema/erythema)', 'Requires prompt treatment to prevent coronary complications.'),
('Multisystem Inflammatory Syndrome in Children (MIS-C)', 'Supportive care (fluids, pressors PRN). IVIG +/- Corticosteroids often used. Screen for cardiac involvement (Echo, troponin, BNP). Anticoagulation considered.', 'NKDA', 'IVIG, IV Methylprednisolone', 'Recent SARS-CoV-2 infection/exposure. Fever, multisystem organ involvement (cardiac, GI, derm, neuro), elevated inflammatory markers (CRP, ESR, ferritin)', 'Requires hospital admission.'),
('Rheumatic Fever, Acute', 'Penicillin (eradicate Strep infection). Aspirin or NSAIDs for arthritis/fever. Corticosteroids for carditis. Long-term Penicillin prophylaxis to prevent recurrence.', 'Penicillin (use alternative)', 'Aspirin high dose initially, Benzathine Penicillin G IM monthly (prophylaxis)', 'Jones criteria met after GAS pharyngitis (Carditis, Arthritis, Chorea, Erythema Marginatum, Subcutaneous Nodules). Elevated ASO titer.', 'Requires long-term follow-up.'),
('Infective Endocarditis', 'Prolonged course IV antibiotics based on organism/susceptibilities (often 4-6 weeks). Surgical valve repair/replacement may be needed. Identify source/portal of entry.', 'NKDA', 'IV Vancomycin + Ceftriaxone (empiric pending cultures)', 'Positive blood cultures, Vegetation on Echocardiogram, Clinical signs (fever, murmur, embolic phenomena - Janeway lesions, Osler nodes)', 'Requires Cardiology/ID consultation.'),
('Pericarditis, Acute', 'NSAIDs (Ibuprofen or Indomethacin) + Colchicine (reduces recurrence). Treat underlying cause if identified. Rest. Monitor for tamponade (rare).', 'Aspirin', 'Ibuprofen 600mg PO TID, Colchicine 0.6mg PO BID x 3 months', 'Clinical diagnosis: Pleuritic chest pain (improves leaning forward), pericardial friction rub, diffuse ST elevation/PR depression on EKG', 'Usually viral or idiopathic.'),
('Myocarditis', 'Supportive care: Manage heart failure (diuretics, ACEi/BB if stable), treat arrhythmias. Avoid NSAIDs. Treat underlying cause if identified (viral, autoimmune). May require advanced therapies (LVAD, transplant) if severe.', 'NKDA', 'Lisinopril, Carvedilol (once stable)', 'Elevated Troponin/CK-MB, EKG changes, Echo shows LV dysfunction. Cardiac MRI diagnostic. Endomyocardial biopsy rarely needed.', 'Inflammation of heart muscle.'),
('Dilated Cardiomyopathy', 'Standard heart failure therapy (ACEi/ARB/ARNI, Beta-blocker, Aldosterone antagonist, SGLT2 inhibitor). Diuretics for congestion. Anticoagulation if AFib or thrombus. Consider ICD/CRT based on EF/QRS duration.', 'NKDA', 'Sacubitril/Valsartan, Carvedilol, Spironolactone, Empagliflozin', 'Echocardiogram: Dilated LV, Reduced EF (<40%)', 'Identify/treat underlying cause if possible (ischemic, viral, toxic, familial).'),
('Hypertrophic Cardiomyopathy (HCM)', 'Beta-blockers or non-dihydropyridine CCB (Verapamil, Diltiazem) for symptoms. Avoid dehydration/vasodilators. Septal reduction therapy (myectomy or alcohol ablation) for severe obstruction. ICD for high-risk patients.', 'NKDA', 'Metoprolol Succinate ER daily', 'Echocardiogram: Asymmetric septal hypertrophy, +/- LV outflow tract obstruction. EKG shows LVH.', 'Genetic counseling recommended.'),
('Restrictive Cardiomyopathy', 'Treat underlying cause (amyloidosis, sarcoidosis, hemochromatosis). Diuretics for congestion. Heart transplant may be option in select cases. Prognosis often poor.', 'NKDA', 'Furosemide PRN edema', 'Echocardiogram: Normal/near normal LV size/EF, impaired diastolic filling, biatrial enlargement', 'Stiff ventricles impair filling.'),
('Arrhythmogenic Right Ventricular Cardiomyopathy (ARVC)', 'Beta-blockers. Antiarrhythmics (Sotalol, Amiodarone). ICD placement usually indicated due to arrhythmia risk. Avoid strenuous exercise.', 'NKDA', 'Metoprolol daily, ICD placed', 'EKG (epsilon waves, TWI), Echo/MRI (RV dilation/dysfunction/fatty infiltration). Genetic testing.', 'Inherited condition causing RV replacement by fat/fibrosis.'),
('Long QT Syndrome (LQTS)', 'Beta-blockers (Nadolol, Propranolol) first-line (except LQT3). Avoid QT-prolonging drugs. ICD placement for high-risk patients (aborted cardiac arrest, syncope). Genetic testing/family screening.', 'NKDA', 'Nadolol daily', 'EKG: Prolonged QTc interval. Genetic testing confirms mutation.', 'Increased risk of Torsades de Pointes/sudden death.'),
('Brugada Syndrome', 'ICD placement is only proven therapy for symptomatic/high-risk patients. Avoid fever, certain medications (sodium channel blockers, psychotropics). Genetic testing/family screening.', 'NKDA', 'ICD placed', 'EKG: Characteristic Type 1 Brugada pattern (coved ST elevation V1-V3). May be intermittent.', 'Increased risk of ventricular fibrillation/sudden death.'),
('Wolff-Parkinson-White (WPW) Syndrome', 'Asymptomatic: Observation vs EP study/ablation. Symptomatic (AVRT): Vagal maneuvers, Adenosine IV, Beta-blocker/CCB (if no AFib). Catheter ablation of accessory pathway curative.', 'NKDA', 'Catheter ablation scheduled', 'EKG: Short PR interval, Delta wave, Wide QRS', 'Accessory pathway predisposes to re-entrant tachycardias.'),
('Supraventricular Tachycardia (SVT) - AVNRT/AVRT', 'Acute: Vagal maneuvers, Adenosine IV STAT. Chronic prevention: Beta-blocker, Calcium channel blocker, or Catheter ablation (often curative).', 'NKDA', 'Metoprolol daily for prevention', 'EKG during episode shows narrow complex tachycardia', 'Patient reports recurrent episodes of rapid palpitations.'),
